We construct an EDHOD model by allowing the central galaxy HOD parameters $M_\text{min}$ and $\sigma_{ \log M_h}$ to have a power-law dependence on $\delta_{1-5}$, in equations:

nexttext:

Note that our EDHOD model has seven parameters, $\{A, B, \gamma, \beta, M_1, M_{\rm cut}, \alpha\} $, whereas the HOD presented in $\S 2$ has five.  (ED)HOD parameters are inferred by  using a downhill simplex method to minimize a sum of squares function, $\sum_i (D^i_\text{model} - D^i_\text{HW13})^2/(D^i_\text{HW13})^2$.  The data vector $\vec{D}$ is  galaxy-correlation function in the range $r=0.1-30 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$ in $30$ equal logarithmic bins, with the total number of galaxies included as an additional fitting point for each sample selection.

Figure \ref{fig:19_xi} shows the results of fitting the $M_r \leq -19$ galaxy sample.  The EDHOD model achieves a good overall fit to the HW13 ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$, with fluctuating deviations up to $\sim 5 \%$ in the region of the 1-halo to 2-halo crossover.  The best-fit HOD model has a large scale offset of $10\%$ in ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ (5 \% in $b_g$); while several HOD parameters can be adjusted to increase the large scale bias, doing so would alter the small scale ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ in a way that worsens the overall fit.  This kind of offset could be a diagnostic for galaxy assembly bias, but we have not explored whether it can be erased by giving more freedom to the assumed radial profile of satellites within halos.  The right panel of Fig. \ref{fig:19_xi} shows ${\xi_{\rm gm}}(r)$ predicted by the HOD or EDHOD model that best fits ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$.  Deviations from the HW13 ${\xi_{\rm gm}}(r)$ are similar to those for ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$, but reduced in magnitude by a factor of two. 

Figure \ref{fig:19_r} compares the cross-correlation coefficients for $M_r \leq -19$ samples in the HW13, HOD, and EDHOD catalogs.  In each case we use the simulation's true ${\xi_{\rm mm}}(r)$ and the ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ and ${\xi_{\rm gm}}(r)$ computed numerically from the corresponding catalog, calculating ${r_{\rm gm}}(r)$ from Eqn. \ref{cross_corr}.  At $r > 1 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$, the EDHOD and HOD models reproduce the HW13 result to 1 \% or better, despite the 5-10 \% deviations in ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$.  For this sample, all three models predict ${r_{\rm gm}}(r)$ very close to one on these scales.  Within the 1-halo regime, the EDHOD and HOD fits continue to track the HW13 result, with deviations of a few percent.  

Figure \ref{fig:rest_xi} shows similar results for the $M_r \leq -20, -21, \; \text{and} \; -21.5$ samples.  Results in $\S$ 2 show that the impact of galaxy assembly bias decreases with increasing luminosity threshold.  Consistent with this behavior, the EDHOD model fits the HW13 ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ substantially better than the global HOD model, but the difference between EDHOD and HOD fits becomes less significant for the higher thresholds.  Results for these brighter, sparser samples become progressively noisier.   As seen previously for $M_r \leq -19$, deviations in ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ are mirrored in ${\xi_{\rm gm}}(r)$, with a factor $\sim 2$ reduction in amplitude. 

Figure \ref{fig:rest_r} shows the cross-correlation coefficients for these higher luminosity samples.  For $M_r \leq -20$ and $M_r \leq -21$, the EDHOD and HOD models again track the HW13 results at $r > 1\; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$, with 1-2 \% deviations in ${r_{\rm gm}}(r)$ that appear consistent with random fluctuations.  In the $M_r \leq -21$ case, this percent-level agreement holds even when ${r_{\rm gm}}(r)$ has climbed to 1.05, so it is not simply a consequence of all three models predicting ${r_{\rm gm}} \approx 1.0$.  For the $M_r \leq -21.5$ samples, results are too noisy for percent-level tests, but there is no evidence for a systematic difference between the HW13 cross-correlation and those predicted by the HOD or EDHOD fits. 

Given measurements of ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ and ${\xi_{\rm gm}}(r)$, and a cross correlation coefficient ${r_{\rm gm}}(r)$ inferred from an HOD or EDHOD model fit, one can calculate the underlying matter correlation function ${\xi_{\rm mm}}(r)$ via Eqn. \ref{mass_inferred}.  (Because GGL constrains ${\Omega_{\rm m}} {\xi_{\rm gm}}$, it is ${\Omega_{\rm m}}^2 {\xi_{\rm mm}}$ that is constrained, but here we omit the $\Omega_\text{m}$ dependence for simplicity.)  

Solid black curves in Fig. \ref{fig:mass_inferred_fit} show the principal results of this paper, the accuracy within which the true matter correlation function of the Bolshoi simulation is recovered by applying this procedure to the ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ and ${\xi_{\rm gm}}(r)$ measurements from the HW13 catalogs, using an EDHOD model to infer ${r_{\rm gm}}(r)$.  For the $M_r \leq -19$ samples, recovery is accurate to better than $2 \%$ for $r > 1 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$.  Deviations for the brighter samples are larger, but they appear consistent with statistical fluctuations.  Deviations are larger inside $1 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$, but not drastically so.  Results for the global HOD fits are similar to those for the EDHOD fits, even though the global HOD model does not produce good fits to ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$.  Grey solid curves in Fig. \ref{fig:mass_inferred_fit} show the results of using the true EDHOD measured directly from the HW13 catalogs (as described in $\S 2$).  Fitting the EDHOD to ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ yields better recovery of ${\xi_{\rm mm}}(r)$ than using the directly measured EDHOD.  

A red galaxy sample presents a stringent test of our methodology because of the strong galaxy assembly bias imprinted by the HW13 age-matching procedure, and secondarily because the HOD paramerization that we use is designed for luminosity threshold samples.  Figure \ref{fig:red_analysis} shows results for the red $M_r \leq -20$ galaxy sample, similar to those shown in Figs. \ref{fig:19_xi}-\ref{fig:mass_inferred_fit} for the luminosity threshold samples.  For red galaxies, the global HOD model produces a poor fit to ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$, with a 10 \% large scale offset and a maximum deviation of 25 \%.  The EDHOD fit has deviations of 5-10 \% in the $1-10 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$ range.   Nonetheless, the EDHOD model matches the HW13 cross-correlation coefficient to 1 \% or better at $r > 2 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$, and to 2 \% or better at $r > 1 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$.  Even for the global HOD model, the agreement in ${r_{\rm gm}}$ is generally better than 3 \% at $r > 1 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$.

The end result, shown in the bottom panel of Fig. \ref{fig:red_analysis}, is that our EDHOD modeling allows recovery of ${\xi_{\rm mm}}(r)$ with accuracy of 2 \% or better at $ r > 2 \; {h^{-1} \text{Mpc}}$ when applied to the $M_r \leq -20$ red galaxy population of the HW13 catalog.  Even though this model does not fully represent the galaxy assembly bias present in the HW13 catalog, errors in ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$ and ${\xi_{\rm gm}}(r)$ cancel in a way that accurately estimates matter clustering.  In contrast to the luminosity-threshold cases shown in Fig. \ref{fig:mass_inferred_fit}, the EDHOD modeling significantly outperforms the global HOD modeling in this case, so the additional complication appears worthwhile at least in situations where the global HOD model yields a poor fit to ${\xi_{\rm gg}}(r)$. 


